en the ages of 12 and 17 Marijuana6 html 2 2 Furthermore the marijuana that is available today can be 5 times more potent than the marijuana of the 1970s Marijuana6 html 3 3 The use of marijuana can produce adverse physical mental emotional and behavioral changes and contrary to popular belief it can be addictive Marijuana smoke like cigarette smoke can harm the lungs Marijuana6 html 4 4 Marijuana6 html 5 5 Marijuana6 html 6 6 The use of marijuana can impair short term memory Marijuana6 html 7 7 Marijuana6 html 8 8 verbal skills Marijuana6 html 9 9 and judgment Marijuana6 html 10 10 and distort perception Marijuana6 html 11 11 Marijuana6 html 12 12 Marijuana6 html 13 13 It also may weaken the immune system Marijuana6 html 14 14 Marijuana6 html 15 15 Marijuana6 html 16 16 Marijuana6 html 17 17 and possibly increase a user s likelihood of developing cancer Marijuana6 html 15 15 Marijuana6 html 18 18 Finally the increasing use of marijuana by very young teens may have a profoundly negative effect upon their development Marijuana6 html 9 9 Marijuana6 html 19 19 Marijuana6 html 20 20 Marijuana6 html 21 21 Marijuana6 html 22 22 We hope that this research report will help make readers aware of our current knowledge of marijuana abuse and its harmful effects Glen R Hanson Ph D D D S Acting Director National Institute on Drug Abuse If you have the Acrobat reader plug in for Netscape or Internet Explorer click on the document link and you will be able to view and or print out the pages If you have trouble viewing the document in your browser window download the document Windows users right click on the link and Save as to your computer and get http www adobe com products acrobat readstep html Adobe Acrobat Reader free in order to view it This report is also available in PDF format PDF RRMarijuana pdf Marijuana Abuse PDF format All materials appearing in the Research Reports Series are in the public domain and may be reproduced without permission from NIDA Citation of the sour